### "Tell me about a time when you got stuck while coding. How did you work your way through the problem?". 

Today tab crash - app animation - failing all the UI flows that interacted with that screen

1. The Situation (The Problem)
"While automating the 'Today' tab of our mobile application, I encountered a persistent and flaky crash. Whenever the automation script navigated to this tab, the Appium session would either time out or the app would crash. After investigation, I realized the 'Today' tab featured a continuous, looping background animation that was preventing the driver from interacting with any elements."

2. The Struggle (The "Stuck" Moment)
"I initially thought it was a standard synchronization issue. I tried adding long Explicit Waits and even Thread.sleep(), but the driver still couldn't 'grab' the elements. Appium's driver server was waiting for the application to reach an 'Idle' or Quiescent State before performing the next action. Because the animation was infinite, the app never stayed idle long enough for Appium to proceed, leading to a session timeout."

3. The Work-Through (The Diagnostic Process)
"I took a three-pronged approach to solve this:

Hierarchy Analysis: I noticed in the Appium logs that the server was stuck on Waiting for idle state. This confirmed that the UI thread was constantly 'busy' due to the animation.

Developer Collaboration: I spoke with the frontend developers to understand how the animation was implemented. We found it was a high-frequency Lottie animation that didn't have a 'pause' state for test environments.

Technical Research: I researched how to bypass the 'Idle' check in the UiAutomator2 driver settings."

4. The Resolution (The iOS Fix)
"I implemented a targeted strategy to bypass Apple’s strict idle checks:

Reduce Quiescence Wait: I used Appium's mobile: setWindowAnimationDuration and the waitForQuiescence setting. By setting waitForQuiescence to false, I forced XCUITest to interact with the elements immediately without waiting for the animation thread to clear.

Capability: options.setWaitForQuiescence(false);

UIView Animation Speed: In our debug builds, I worked with the developers to set window.layer.speed = 0; or UIView.setAnimationsEnabled(false); when the app detects a test environment. This effectively 'freezes' the animation at its first frame, making the UI thread instantly quiescent for the driver."

5. The Result
"This reduced our iOS test execution time for that specific module by 15 seconds per test, as we no longer had to wait for the XCUITest driver to time out its internal 'idle' checks. It taught me that on iOS, testability often requires slowing down or stopping the UI to match the speed of the automation driver.


